Remove code duplicates and make the code a little more consistent

Fix deriveClass

derive declarations for JavaType, ArrayElement, and Exceptional shares
the same code.

For native classes, deriveClass "Exceptional" always generates
'TApp _ (TCon _ _)'
even when 'instrho' (encodes "Bar" in "derive Foo Bar") has type
variable(s).

This commit replaces the relevant piece of code by working one.
By this change, 'SName's contained in the result value may have 'Simple'
names instead of always having 'With1' names. Nevertheless, it appears
to be working fine.

Confirmed tests/comp/Issue332.fr compiles.

The following commit will tidy up the code to remove duplicates.

Find the cause by putting traces, etc.

Line numbers are of the current master
(9d2c8cc195a4f2c0a2093b26f3b5ee3e09cdb617).
(Not of this commit)

tl;dr The cause is that unconditionally setting TCon at
frege/compiler/passes/Instances.fr:364

The error is produced in frege.compiler.tc.Util.unify (:340)
Because f.c.tc.Util.unified (:337) returns false
See params.json for the parameters of unify
According to this, both t1 and t2 are TApp, but the second part of t1 is
TApp whereas that of t2 is TCon. Because of this, they fail to match the
case expression in unified, leading to returning false.

Studied why the second part of t2 becomes TCon by examining how "derive
JavaType" is processed.
Flow of processes:
"derive" (source text) -> DERIVE :: TokenID -> DrvDcl :: DefinitionS

At f.c.passes.Instances.deriveInst (:53), both DrvDcl and "JavaType"
appears.

Examined its result value (deriveInst-dcls.json) to find [NatDcl.txs]
has the same info as the t2 mentioned above, modulo name resolution.

By tracing deriveDcls (deriveDcls/trace.fr), which produces the result
value of deriveInst, I discovered that at Instances.fr:364:
tapp in deriveClass "Exceptional" in deriveClass,
unconditionally sets TCon for the second part of TApp, producing a
incorrect result value.

Compare packages in linkHere

Compares the package name in an import declaration and that of the
resolved symbol. If they differ, regards the symbol as re-exported one

Finish the Monad hierarchy.

'return' and 'pure' are now different functions who do the same
but are differently typed. If you use 'return', you'll get a
'Monad' constraint. OTOH, if you want to define an 'Applicative'
instance, you must use 'pure'. And when you use 'pure' in code,
you get an 'Applicative' constraint (unless otherwise specified
or superseded by use of functions that already have a 'Monad'
constraint.)

This is so that a do block that uses only (>>=) and 'return'
gets a 'Monad' constraint, instead of 'Applicative' and 'Bind'
constraints (which most often leads to passing the very same 'Monad'
constraint twice on the use side).

You can write a forall (including overloading) in a type synonym,
thus for example:

In contrast to Haskell, you cannot apply a type synonym to a forall type.

Fix for issue #49

Typechecking has been enhanced in many places to deal properly with
higher rank polymorphic functions with constraints.

In code generation, we now treat lambda and pattern arguments of
higher ranked functions as uninstantiated with regard to constraints.

This means that every expression that gets passed for such functions
will be wrapped in a lambda that accepts the needed constraints,
except if it is itself a lmbda bound function of the same type.

When such a function is actually applied, the current constraints are appled first
before the arguments.

This enhances typechecking in the case where the left hand side is a single identifier and the right hand side is a partial application of a higher rank function up to, but excluding, the polymorphic function argument or just that function. This used to give type errors, but now infers the higher rank type.

Hence if we have

  bar :: Bool -> (forall.[a]->[a]) -> [b] -> [b]

the following is ok:

  foo = bar       -- foo :: Bool -> (forall.[a]->[a]) -> [b] -> [b]
  baz = bar true  -- baz :: (forall.[a]->[a]) -> [b] -> [b]

while this is wrong:

  wrong f = bar true f

This is just like it works in GHC, according to my tests.

In addition, a lambda argument containing a forall type will cause the lambda to have higher rank type.
This fixes in part issue #47, however, the problem remains as higher rank types from
somewhere else (like a case) are still not passed upwards.

versioning

- frege/Version.fr will be created through perl script mkversion.pl
everytime the HEAD of the current branch changes
- it contains the number of snapshots since the beginning of versioned
history
- version number is constructed from this in frege.compiler.Main, which
imports frege.Version
- the frege/Version.fr itself is **not** tracked in git.
